<h1>Student Case Studies</h1>
<h3>Anupama Handoo&nbsp;&nbsp;MSc Urban Water and Environmental Management<br />
  </h3>
<p><img src="Images/anupama.jpg" alt="Anupama Handoo" width="210" height="140" hspace="2" border="1" align="left" />Hi, I'm Anupama Handoo and I'm studying for a Masters of Science degree in Urban Water and Environmental Management. I am one of the many international students at the University of Abertay, Dundee and chose to come here because of the excellence of the School of Contemporary Sciences. <br />
    <br />
  I grew up in Jammu and Kashmir in India and graduated as top of my class with a Bachelor of Engineering degree. I have always wanted to go into civil engineering because I'm fascinated by the challenge of balancing vital development with respect for the environment. Engineering is also such a highly respected profession, and one where I can make my mark, helped by my qualification from Abertay.</p>
<p>When I graduated I spent some time working in the IT industry in India but I recognised that I want to build my career in environmental management and engineering. When I was considering where to study I was offered a place at four UK universities. I chose Abertay because it has an international reputation for the quality of its Environmental Science teaching.</p>
<p>As a small and modern university Abertay gives me great access to teaching and facilities. The classes are small - there are 27 Masters students on my course and 13 of them are international - and the University has such an excellent approach to studying. It's a collaboration between the academic staff and students, with real emphasis being placed on what you can learn and discover for yourself. There's great interdisciplinary work, with a chance to draw on all of the University's excellence, from computing to business.</p>
<p>Before I came here I didn't know a lot about Dundee. It's a beautiful city, full of life and light, and I'm enjoying living here in the University's accommodation. Perhaps because I come from Jammu and Kashmir I am used to the mountains and the occasional winter snow!</p>
<p>In the future I want to build my career internationally. Civil engineering and environmental challenges will be very important in the twenty-first century and I'm sure that the experience and qualification I have gained at Abertay will allow me to tackle these challenges and make a positive contribution to the world.</p>
<h3>Gayle Duncan&nbsp;&nbsp;BSc Hons Biological Sciences</h3>
<p><img src="Images/gayle.jpg" alt="Gayle Duncan" width="210" height="140" hspace="2" border="1" align="left" />I'm in my fourth year studying Biological Sciences in the School of Contemporary Sciences at the University of Abertay, Dundee and my name is Gayle Duncan. <br />
    <br />
  I come from Blairgowrie, not far from Dundee, and travel to and fro every day. I'm proud that I'm the first member of my family to go to University, and living at home keeps me close to them but allows me to take part in all of the life as a student at Abertay. It's also cheaper, which is great, and Dundee is one of the least expensive places to study. My mum and I teach dancing and I run my own cheerleading team here so it's perfect to be able to have my home and student life together.</p>
<p>I took my Highers in Biology, Human Biology, Chemistry and Maths. Originally I wanted to study anatomy and started on a course at another Tayside university. I didn't enjoy it and after six months switched to Abertay. I have never regretted it for a moment! Abertay is excellent because it has small class sizes and loads of emphasis on practical work. The lecturers are really friendly and I feel that the quality of education is therefore so much better. The courses make use of the excellent opportunities offered by the other Schools, and I've studied business, marketing and IT as well. There's a lot more emphasis on your coursework and ongoing assessment rather than a huge bank of exams - it's hard work, but great!</p>
<p>Abertay is fantastic at arranging placements and field trips. During my course we've made six field trips, looking at firms that work in the biological sciences industry. Best of all, last summer Abertay helped me to get an internship as a researcher at the University of Virginia in the US for ten weeks. It was a fantastic opportunity: I was based in the Department of Biomedical Engineering, working on nanotechnology and cellular biomechanics. </p>
<p>These technologies will be so important in the twenty-first century and it's very much part of Abertay's success that I have been able to study such cutting-edge science. Right now I am deciding whether to take a post-graduate degree or work in industry. The University has a great careers service and if I do take a further degree I'll definitely study at Abertay because I love it here - and thanks to the internship in the US I have made some great contacts there too. </p>
<p>Because I have enjoyed my time here I work with local schools and go out to talk about Abertay and what an excellent education you get here. I can't recommend it enough - it's been the best four years of my life!</p>
<h3>Gregor McMaster&nbsp;&nbsp;BSc Hons Food &amp; Consumer Sciences</h3>
<p><img src="Images/gregor.jpg" alt="Gregor McMaster" width="133" height="210" hspace="2" border="1" align="left" />My name is Gregor McMaster and I'm in my fourth year of a BSc in Food and Consumer Sciences. <br />
    <br />
  I'm originally from Dundee and went to school in Monifieth. There are two things I'm really passionate about - football and food - and I've been really lucky to be able to be involved with both at Abertay. I took a Higher in Health and Food Technology and worked as a part-time chef which really spurred my interest in food - Abertay was the only University I applied to because of its reputation and because there is such a wide scope of jobs open to you with this degree. <br />
  <br />
  In my first three years here I played semi-professional football with a local club, which was great - I could easily balance the pressures of my academic work with sport. In my final year I've been focusing on my degree so I've been playing for the University team. I'm really proud to be representing the Uni. There's a great team spirit - it's really friendly and open and of course there's a great social side too, with all the different sports' teams at Abertay. I regret not getting involved earlier now!</p>
<p>The course has been excellent. The first two years gives you the basis to work on and draws on all of the excellence at Abertay, with teaching from all of the University's Schools in areas like IT and marketing. You then focus on your industry with really relevant and open teaching. The standard is high and support from the lecturers is always good, with a small number of students - around 30 -making the teaching really personal. The School organises fantastic vocational placements as well. I spent 10 weeks with the Scottish chef Christopher Trotter, using wonderful fresh Scottish food. I learnt so much - I've also been really lucky and worked with him on a major new cookbook which is about to be published, researching and updating 300 year-old Scottish recipes.</p>
<p>Abertay is a fantastic place to study and I'd recommend getting involved in University activities and living in halls to really make the most of it. There's a great student atmosphere and a good international mix. I came here at 17 and have loved it ever since. I like the sense that it is always developing and improving - it's constantly getting better with upgrading of everything from IT equipment to student's rooms going on all the time. It's so encouraging to see it. The specialist focus of the courses available makes it excellent as well- I really can't fault the Uni.</p>
<p>I want to go on to work with food in my career, perhaps in magazines and commercials, and the qualifications and experience I've gained at Abertay could not give me a better start.</p>
